      "elements"     :[
        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el01",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"intro",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"David is 43. He runs a small business, has two teenage children, and is an elder at his church. By any measure, his life is full and productive. He doesn't seem like a man with a problem. But David has a habit. It started eight years ago: a way of decompressing after particularly brutal weeks at work. At the time it felt harmless, even reasonable. He wasn't hurting anyone. Just unwinding.\n\nEight years later, the habit is no longer something David chooses. It chooses him. It shows up when he is tired, when a deal falls through, when he and his wife argue, when the elders' meeting runs long and ends badly, when he feels – as he often does – that he is holding too many things together with not enough help. And increasingly, it shows up for no reason at all: just the pull of it, familiar and reliable, in the quiet of a weekday evening.\n\nDavid has tried to stop many times. He has prayed, confessed (to God, if not to anyone else), and resolved with complete sincerity that this time will be different. Sometimes it is – for a few weeks, occasionally a few months. But he always goes back. And each time the shame is a little heavier, and the secret a little more sealed, and the gap between the David that people see on Sunday morning and the David who sits alone on Tuesday night grows a little wider.\n\nWhat David wants, more than anything, is to be free. What he can't yet see is that freedom won't come through trying harder. It comes through something far more fundamental: a change in what his heart reaches for. This series is written to help people like David – and people whose stories look very different from David's – find that change. Maybe you recognise something of yourself in David. Or maybe your struggle looks different – a different behaviour, a different trigger, a different history. Before we go any further, it is worth asking an honest question.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

