        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el17",
          "type"         :"callout",
          "subtype"      :"misunderstanding",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"Idolatry",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>What do you think of when you hear this word?</li><li>Does it feel like an ancient problem, or a modern one?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>Idolatry tends to conjure images of people bowing to golden statues – a problem belonging to other religions, or other centuries. It can feel like one of the least relevant words in the Bible.</p><p>But the biblical concept is more precise and more uncomfortable than that. An idol is anything that takes God's place at the centre of the heart – anything we trust to give us what only God can truly provide. It doesn't need a physical form. It just needs our deepest loyalty.</p><p>Paul's claim in Ephesians 5:5 is striking: greed – compulsive wanting – <em>is</em> idolatry. The idol isn't a statue. It's the thing you keep returning to, the thing you protect, the thing that promises to make life work.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el18",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"There's a more precise way to describe what happens in the heart when we're caught in addictive behaviour: idolatry. Paul makes a striking claim: sexual sin and compulsive desire are not primarily rule-breaking. They are misplaced worship. Something has taken God's place at the centre of the heart.\n\nThis isn't a metaphor. It describes something that is really happening. When I return again and again to my addiction – when I find myself thinking about it, planning for it, protecting it, defending it even when I hate myself for doing so – I am relating to it the way a worshipper relates to a god.\n\nAugustine saw this with painful clarity: 'I was seeking you outside myself, and finding not the God of my heart.' The longing that drives us to our addictions is not, at root, a longing for the addiction itself. It is a longing for something real – for worth, for love, for rest, for safety, for pleasure, for justice, for cleansing – that God alone can truly provide. We are not seeking too much. We are seeking the right things in the wrong places.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el19",
          "type"         :"biblePassage",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "bibleRef"     :"Ephesians 5:5",
          "translation"  :"NET",
          "passageText"  :"<sup>5</sup>For you can be confident of this one thing: that no person who is immoral, impure, or greedy (such a person is an idolater) has any inheritance in the kingdom of Christ and God.",
          "passageUrl"   :"https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Ephesians+5&version=NET",
          "bottomPadding":"none"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el20",
          "type"         :"callout",
          "subtype"      :"misunderstanding",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"Willpower",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>Do you think willpower is the answer to habitual sin?</li><li>Why does it so often fail – even when the desire to change is genuine?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>Willpower is the default solution most people reach for. Try harder. Be more disciplined. Make better decisions. And when it fails – as it usually does, eventually – the conclusion is: <em>I didn't try hard enough.</em></p><p>But willpower operates at the level of behaviour. The problem, as this chapter argues, is at the level of desire. You cannot, by an act of will, change what you want. You can override a desire for a time – but a suppressed desire is a pressurised desire. It will find a way out.</p><p>This isn't an excuse for passivity. It's a diagnosis that points to the right cure: not more effort, but a reordering of what the heart loves. That is the work of the Gospel, not the work of the will.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

