        {
          "elementId"    :"ch01-el24",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Addictive behaviours work by making real promises about real needs. The needs themselves are not the problem – they are God-given, built into us by design. The problem is where we go to meet them. And the reason we go to our addictions rather than to God is not simply that we are weak or morally deficient. It is that, at some level, we believe the addiction will deliver what God has not.\n\nKnowledge doesn't automatically produce change. That's because willpower works on the level of behaviour, while the problem is on the level of desire. We cannot, by an act of will, change what we want. We can override our desires for a time – but a suppressed desire is a pressurised desire. It will find a way out.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

