          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Sarah is a family doctor. She is also a mother of three, a church small group leader, and the kind of person other people describe as 'having it all together.' She is the first to arrive and the last to leave. She never misses a deadline, never drops a ball, never lets anyone down – not professionally, not domestically, not at church.\n\nWhat nobody sees is that Sarah has not stopped for fifteen years. Never really stopped. Her busyness is not incidental – it is structural. It is the architecture of her life, and she built it carefully, because she discovered early on that when she keeps moving, the voice stays quiet. The voice that says: 'Is this enough? Are you enough? What would people think if they could really see you?'\n\nWhen Sarah does stop – when she's forced to – the anxiety is immediate and physical. So she fills the gap. Another project, another commitment, another reason to be indispensable. Her addiction does not look like an addiction. It looks like virtue. But it is doing the same work as any other: it keeps a deep and scary question at bay.",
