          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"The fear of man takes many forms. Sometimes it drives public behaviour – the need to be seen as successful, capable, spiritual, indispensable. Sometimes it drives private behaviour instead – the creation of a secret world in which, whatever failures exist in real life, success is guaranteed. What all of these have in common is that they are, at some level, performances for an imagined audience. They create a theatre in which the verdict is always favourable.\n\nThere's an irony here. The people most visibly caught in the Respect dynamic are those who look least like they have a problem: the high-achieving professional, the effective church leader, the person whose busyness and competence are genuinely admired. Their addiction is invisible precisely because it dresses up as virtue. But drivenness of this kind – where the inability to rest, the terror of being found inadequate, and the compulsive filling of every gap are the engine beneath the achievement – is doing the same work as any other compulsion: it is a flight from an unbearable question.\n\nThe point is not that effectiveness and fear-driven compulsion are the same thing, or that every high achiever is hiding a problem. Many people work hard from healthy motivations. The question worth asking is not what you achieve, but what is driving you – and whether you could stop if you chose to.",
