        {
          "elementId"    :"ch03-el01",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"intro",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Marcus is 31. He is thoughtful, well-liked, and – by his own account – terrible at relationships. Not in an obvious way. He is warm, funny, interested in people. He has many acquaintances and a few people he calls friends. But genuine intimacy – where someone knows the full truth of you and stays anyway – has always felt just out of reach.\n\nHe is not sure exactly when porn became a habit. It was gradual. What he is sure of is what it gave him, in the early days at least: a feeling of being wanted. Of being, in some imagined way, chosen. It sounds absurd when he says it out loud. But the feeling was real.\n\nWhat Marcus could not see – what took him years to begin to understand – is that the thing he was using to medicate his loneliness was making the loneliness worse. Every hour spent in that private world was an hour not spent building the real relationships he actually needed. The false intimacy was crowding out the real thing, and the gap between his outer sociability and his inner isolation was growing wider every year.",
