          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"There is a specific version of the relationship dynamic that is worth naming directly. For many people, the appeal of pornography – and of some other addictive behaviours – is not simply that it offers intimacy, but that it offers intimacy on their own terms. It is relational experience without vulnerability, without negotiation, without the possibility of rejection or disappointment. What this amounts to is a desire for sovereignty over our relational world.\n\nOne person described the dynamic with unusual honesty: 'For me, porn is all about the illusion of controlling others. I felt so out of control in my life that this was something I could control. There is no vulnerability, no risk, and therefore, no growth.' The last phrase is telling: no growth. The controlled, risk-free substitute for intimacy actively prevents the development of the capacity for real relationship. We practise cowardice and wonder why we never become brave.",
