          "text"         :"Two people. Two very different stories. Anne is fifty-six. Three years ago her husband died after a long illness. The grief was – still is – enormous. What surprised her was how quickly she found that a glass of wine in the evening took the edge off it. Not removed it. Just made it bearable. Then two glasses. Then the bottle was open anyway. Her GP, when she finally mentioned it, was kind but clear: what had started as self-medication had become dependency. Anne does not think of herself as someone with a drinking problem. She thinks of herself as someone with a grief problem who found something that helped – until it didn't.\n\nDaniel is twenty-seven. His life is, by most measures, fine. Good job, good friends, no particular crisis. But most evenings, after dinner, he picks up his phone. He is not sure exactly when this became the thing he does – it just is, now. An hour on social media, maybe more. He is not enjoying it, exactly. He is barely aware of it. But the thought of stopping, of sitting in a quiet room with nothing in his hands, produces a faint but real anxiety that he has never quite examined. The phone is not a pleasure. It is a place. And without it, the evenings feel formless and strange.\n\nAnne and Daniel are looking for different things. Anne wants the pain to stop. Daniel wants the emptiness to be filled. But both have found, in their different ways, a behaviour that answers a need – and both are now more bound to it than they intended to be.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
