          "text"         :"Ryan is 38. He works long hours in a demanding job, has two young children, a mortgage, and a marriage that is – his word – 'strained.' He's not a bad husband or father. By most measures he's responsible. But every evening, after the children are in bed, he disappears.\n\nNot literally – he's in the spare room, in front of a screen, playing an online game he has played for years. In there, the rules are clear, the objectives are defined, and progress is measurable. Nobody needs anything from him that he can't provide. Nobody is disappointed in him. The pressure – the relentless, accumulating pressure of being a father and a husband and an employee and a functioning adult – simply does not exist in there.\n\nHis wife has stopped asking when he is coming to bed. She already knows. Ryan does not think of himself as having a problem. He thinks of himself as having a way of coping. The distinction, he is beginning to suspect, may be less clear than he thought.",
