          "question"     :"<ul><li>What do you think Christianity teaches about pleasure?</li><li>Does following Jesus mean wanting less?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>Asceticism is the belief that physical pleasure is spiritually dangerous, and that holiness requires suppressing or denying the body's desires. It has appeared in various forms throughout Christian history, and colours many people's instinctive sense of what a serious Christian should look like: austere, self-denying, suspicious of enjoyment.</p><p>But this is not the Bible's picture. The God of Scripture made a world overflowing with good things and declared it very good. He is described as one who 'richly provides us with everything for our enjoyment' (1 Tim 6:17). The problem is never that we desire pleasure. The problem is where we go to find it.</p><p>This chapter's argument is not 'want less.' It is 'want more truly' – to find the real thing rather than the counterfeit.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
