          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"intro",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Tom's been married for 11 years. The marriage isn't what he'd hoped for. There is distance, disappointment, and a low-level resentment. On the evenings when the distance feels sharp, Tom finds himself on his phone. He wouldn't describe what he does as revenge. But beneath the surface, there is this thought: she's not giving me what I need, so I'll take it somewhere else. That's what she gets.\n\nRachel has been a Christian since her teens. She knows the gospel, and has taught it to others. But she has never quite been able to apply it to herself. The sins of her past sit on her like a weight that forgiveness never quite lifts. And so she returns, again and again, to a behaviour she hates. Not because it brings her pleasure. Because, in a way she can't fully articulate, it's what she deserves. The shame is not a side-effect of the behaviour. It is, in some dark sense, the point.\n\nTom and Rachel are not obvious companions. One is angry; the other is drowning. One reaches out; the other turns inward. But they share a root – a distorted account of what they deserve, and a failure to receive the grace that is the Gospel's final word on that question.",
