          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"Atonement",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>What do you think of when you hear this word?</li><li>What do you think it means for Christ to have 'atoned' for sin?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>Atonement is sometimes understood as a vague word for forgiveness, or as Christ demonstrating solidarity with human suffering. More commonly, people understand it in everyday terms: to atone for something is to make up for it – to apologise, make amends, or do enough good to balance out the bad.</p><p>But the theological meaning is more specific. Atonement describes the satisfaction of a debt before God – the penalty for sin being paid in full, by a substitute, so that it no longer stands against us. Hebrews 10 captures it in a single image: Christ, having offered one sacrifice for sins for all time, <em>sat down</em>. The posture of completed work. Nothing left to add.</p><p>This matters directly for this chapter. The person using their addiction as self-punishment is, in effect, attempting their own atonement – paying a debt they cannot believe has already been paid. The Gospel's answer is not 'try harder.' It is: the priest has sat down.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

