        {
          "elementId"    :"ch07-el46",
          "type"         :"callout",
          "subtype"      :"misunderstanding",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"Shame and Guilt",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>Do you think shame and guilt are the same thing?</li><li>What is the difference, if any?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>Shame and guilt are often used as synonyms, but they describe quite different experiences – and the Gospel speaks to them differently.</p><p><b>Guilt</b> says: <em>I have done something wrong.</em> It is a verdict on an action. It is specific, and it is resolved by confession and forgiveness. When guilt is dealt with, the weight lifts.</p><p><b>Shame</b> says: <em>I am something wrong.</em> It is a verdict on the self – on identity, not just behaviour. It is resistant to simple forgiveness, because forgiveness addresses what you did, while shame is about who you are.</p><p>The Gospel speaks to both – but differently. To guilt it says: your sins are forgiven. To shame it says something deeper: you are a beloved child. Not merely acquitted – adopted. Understanding the difference is essential for understanding Rachel's story in this chapter.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

