          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"The Means of Grace",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>Have you heard this phrase before?</li><li>What do you think it refers to?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>'The means of grace' is traditional theological language for the ordinary practices through which God typically works to transform his people: Scripture, prayer, worship, the Lord's Supper, Christian community, sabbath rest, and service of others.</p><p>The phrase can sound mechanical – as if these are levers you pull to produce spiritual results. But that is precisely the misunderstanding. They are not magic. They do not work automatically. They are the normal channels through which the Spirit does his work – and neglecting them while expecting change is like complaining about being hungry while refusing to eat.</p><p>They are also not a substitute for the Gospel. The means of grace do not save us or sanctify us by their own power. They are the soil in which the Spirit works. The person engaging seriously with them over time is giving the Spirit the conditions he typically uses. The person neglecting them is, in effect, asking God to work without the tools he has chosen.</p>",
