      "elements"     :[
        {
          "elementId"    :"ch09-el01",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"intro",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Michael has been sober for 14 months. He knows, with the clarity that only those in recovery possess, that he didn't get there alone.\n\nThere was the Tuesday night group – five men from his church who knew the real shape of his struggle, not the edited version. There was the friend who answered the phone at 11pm on a Thursday when the pull was almost irresistible. There was the pastor who didn't flinch when Michael finally told him everything, and who said, simply: let's bring this to Christ together. There were the ordinary practices – the daily reading, the weekly gathering, the deliberate restructuring of the evenings that used to be his most dangerous hours.\n\nMichael would be the first to say that the theology mattered – that understanding why he was reaching for the bottle, and what God was offering instead, was not incidental to his recovery but central to it. But he would also say this: if he had tried to walk it out alone, he would not have walked it out.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch09-el02",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Western individualism has thoroughly infected the Church. We believe in personal salvation, personal quiet times, personal sin management. We treat our struggles as private matters – to be dealt with between ourselves and God, and revealed to others only when we have achieved sufficient victory to make the telling safe.\n\nThe Bible expects a communal framework for the life of faith. The Christian life is not a solo project with occasional group check-ins. It's a fundamentally shared life – a body, a family, a community of people who are being transformed together.\n\nThe person who tries to walk the road of recovery alone isn't being strong. They're being disobedient – refusing the form of life that God has designed for his people, precisely because he knows we can't do this alone.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

