          "term"         :"Confession",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>What do you think of when you hear this word?</li><li>Is it something Christians do – and to whom?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>For many Protestants, confession means confessing directly to God in private prayer – and nothing more. The idea of confessing to another person may feel either Catholic (sacramental, requiring a priest) or simply unnecessary: God has forgiven me; why does anyone else need to know?</p><p>But James 5:16 is clear: 'Confess your sins to one another and pray for one another so that you may be healed.' The command is mutual and horizontal, not just vertical. It assumes that something happens in the presence of another human being that does not happen in private prayer alone.</p><p>This chapter argues that bringing our struggle into the light before another person is not just therapeutically useful – it is spiritually significant. It is an act of humility that breaks shame's power, and it enacts the Gospel: we are fully known, and not rejected.</p>",
