          "question"     :"<ul><li>What do you think of when you hear this word in a church context?</li><li>Have you experienced it – and what was it like?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>In church culture, 'accountability' often means having someone who occasionally asks 'how are you doing?' – and accepting 'fine' as an answer. At its worst, it means surveillance: someone checking up on you to make sure you haven't failed, with disappointment as the consequence if you have.</p><p>Neither of these is what this chapter means. True accountability involves a specific person who knows the real shape of the struggle (not a sanitised version), asks hard questions, hears honest answers, and responds to failure with 'let's bring this to Christ' rather than judgment.</p><p>The goal is not behavioural compliance. It is relationship – the experience of being fully known and not rejected. That is both a foretaste of the Gospel and a direct antidote to the false intimacy that addiction offers.</p>",
