      "elements"     :[
        {
          "elementId"    :"ch10-el01",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"intro",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Emma came to the first session of this series because her small group leader suggested it, and she couldn't think of a good reason to say no. She was not, she told herself, the kind of person this series was for. She didn't have an addiction. She had a habit – a fairly manageable one, most of the time – and a vague, persistent sense that she was not quite living the life she was supposed to be living.\n\nTen sessions later, Emma would tell you that she was wrong about almost all of that. She did have an addiction – or something close enough to one that the distinction no longer felt important. She recognised herself, with uncomfortable precision, in the Rhythm chapter and the Rescue chapter and, to her considerable surprise, in the Revenge chapter as well. She understood, for the first time, what her habit had been offering her and why willpower alone had never been enough to resist it.\n\nBut the thing she would most want to tell you – the thing that surprised her most – is this: the series did not primarily make her feel worse about the thing she was doing. It made her feel better about God. It gave her a vision of him – as the true source of everything she had been looking for in the wrong places – that was bigger and more beautiful than the vision she had arrived with. And that vision, more than anything else, is what has begun to change her.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch10-el02",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"One of the subtle dangers in recovery is stopping too soon – treating freedom from addiction as the goal, and, once some freedom has been achieved, settling there. Freedom from addiction is good. It is worth fighting for, worth celebrating. But it is not the final destination. It is the clearing away of an obstacle so that the real journey can begin. Sobriety without transformation is an empty achievement in the end. The goal is not the absence of addiction. It is the presence of something better.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

