          "subtype"      :"misunderstanding",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "eyebrow"      :"Common Misunderstanding",
          "term"         :"The 'Already' and the 'Not Yet'",
          "question"     :"<ul><li>Have you heard this phrase before?</li><li>What do you think it means for the Christian life?</li><li>Think of your own answer first, then look at ours.</li></ul>",
          "answer"       :"<p>The 'already and not yet' is theological shorthand for a real tension that every Christian lives in. Christ has come. Sin's power has been broken. The Spirit has been given. The Kingdom of God has genuinely arrived. That's the 'already.'</p><p>And yet: we still struggle. We still suffer. We still sin. The Kingdom is not yet fully here. Creation itself is still groaning. That's the 'not yet.'</p><p>Both are true simultaneously – and getting them wrong in either direction causes real damage. Overemphasising the 'already' produces unrealistic expectations and despair when change is slow. Overemphasising the 'not yet' produces passivity and an excuse for not engaging seriously with growth. The Christian life is lived in the tension between the two.</p>",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch10-el28",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"We need to be clear about a tension that will not be resolved this side of eternity. The Kingdom of God has come in Christ. Sin's power has been broken. The Spirit has been given. New creation has begun. These are accomplished facts, and they are the ground of genuine hope and genuine change.\n\nAnd yet the Kingdom is not fully here. We still struggle. We still suffer. The 'already' gives us real resources and real victories. The 'not yet' explains why the struggle is still hard, and why patience is not optional.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

